<seg id="2281">There are many graphical tools to compare. so why & kdiff3;? let me explain briefly why I wrote.</seg>
<seg id="2282">The merge was very complicated, because one of the contributors made many changes and at the same time corrected the indentation at many places. another programmer had changed a lot of text in the same file.</seg>
<seg id="2283">The program I used showed me only the changed lines, but I could not see what had changed within these lines. and there was no clues to the places where perhaps only the indentation had changed. merging these changes was a small nightmare.</seg>
<seg id="2284">This was the beginning. the first version of & kdiff3; could represent differences within a line and changes to white characters. later, a lot of other useful functions were added.</seg>
<seg id="2285">For example, if you want to quickly compare text, simply copy it to the clipboard and paste it into one of the comparison windows.</seg>
<seg id="2286">A function that made a lot of work was the same and merging of folders. this function converted & kdiff3; almost to a full-fledged file browser.</seg>
<seg id="2287">This is useful when two persons work independently from one piece of code and make changes. the original file (the base) helps to resolve conflicts and simultaneously shows the expected result. in this editor you can even edit the result directly. the screen shot shows three source files when merging:</seg>
<seg id="2288">& kdiff3; also helps you to compare and merge complete folders. this screen shot shows & kdiff3; in the folder:</seg>
<seg id="2289">& kdiff3; displays the exact differences and contrasts with the possibilities of today's color monitors. if you need to check code frequently, you will like this function.</seg>
<seg id="2290">Differences in white characters and tabs are displayed visible. if lines differ only in a certain number of white characters, one can see it at a glance at the summary in the column on the left side. (no more trouble if Someone changes the indentation.)</seg>
<seg id="2291">If a file is the same, and the other one differs in one line, the color indicates which file is different. red color means that both are different.</seg>
<seg id="2292">If all files have the same name but are in different folders, then you can ease typing by writing only the filename of the first file. for example:</seg>
<seg id="2293">1 Folder 1 Folder 2 Folder 2 folder 1 folder 2 folder 2 folder 2 folder 2 folder 2 folder 2 folder 2 folder 2 folder 2 folder 2 folder</seg>
<seg id="2294">Open dialog enables manual typing of file names, selecting a file browser (file...) or selecting a last opened file from the drop-down list. the Open dialog will remember your selection and will show it again next time. you don't have to specify a third file; if you leave the entry for C empty, analyzing the differences with two files will be performed.</seg>
<seg id="2295">Via the Folder Button... you can also select a folder. if you select a folder, the same or merge of folders is initiated. if a file is selected for A, but for B and C a folder, then use & kdiff3; the file name from A in the other two folders.</seg>
<seg id="2296">When merging is checked, the input field is active for target and can be edited. however, it is not absolutely necessary to immediately specify an output file. you can also do this later when saving.</seg>
<seg id="2297">The Setup dialog opens a dialog with Settings. here you can set options before starting the same / merge.</seg>
<seg id="2298">Sometimes you don't want to compare a whole file, but only parts of a text. & kdiff3; allows you to drag text parts from the clipboard into the active comparison window. the comparison begins immediately. in Open dialog you do not need to select files, you can simply close the dialog with the Cancel button.</seg>
<seg id="2299">You can also use drag and drop: simply drag a file from a file manager or selected text from an editor and let it drop over a comparison window.</seg>
<seg id="2300">What is the idea behind it? sometimes a file contains several similar functions. if you want to find out how similar these functions are, it would be a relatively big effort. you just need to create two appropriate files, load them in & kdiff3; then you can easily copy, paste and compare the relevant sections.</seg>
<seg id="2301">Note: currently, you can remove nothing from & kdiff3; only dropping text into a comparison window is supported.</seg>
